quran[185]{c,v,t}:
  17,1,"Celebrated be the praises of Him who took His servant a journey by night from the Sacred Mosque, to the Remote Mosque, the precinct of which we have blessed, to show him of our signs! verily, He both hears and looks"
  17,2,"And we gave Moses the Book and made it a guidance to the children of Israel: 'Take ye to no guardian but me"
  17,3,"Seed of those we bore with Noah (in the ark)! verily, he was a thankful servant"
  17,4,"And we decreed to the children of Israel in the Book, 'Ye shall verily do evil in the earth twice, and ye shall rise to a great height (of pride)"
  17,5,"And when the threat for the first (sin) of the two came, we sent over them servants of ours, endued with violence, and they searched inside your houses; and it was an accomplished threat"
  17,6,"Then we rallied you once more against them, and aided you with wealth and sons, and made you a numerous band"
  17,7,"If ye do well, ye will do well to your own souls; and if ye do ill, it is against them! 'And when the threat for the last came - to harm your faces and to enter the mosque as they entered it the first time, and to destroy what they had got the upper-hand over with utter destruction"
  17,8,"It may be that thy Lord will have mercy on you;- but if ye return we will return, and we have made hell a prison for the misbelievers"
  17,9,"Verily, this Qur'an guides to the straightest path, and gives the glad tidings to the believers who do aright that for them is a great hire"
  17,10,"and that for those who believe not in the hereafter, we have prepared a mighty woe"
  17,11,Man prays for evil as he prays for good; and man was ever hasty
  17,12,"We made the night and the day two signs; and we blot out the sign of the night and make the sign of the day visible, that ye may seek after plenty from your Lord, and that ye may number the years and the reckoning; and we have detailed everything in detail"
  17,13,And every man's augury have we fastened on his neck; and we will bring forth for him on the resurrection day a book offered to him wide open
  17,14,"Read thy book, thou art accountant enough against thyself today"
  17,15,"He who accepts guidance, accepts it only for his own soul: and he who errs, errs only against it; nor shall one burdened soul bear the burden of another. Nor would we punish until we had sent an apostle"
  17,16,And when we desired to destroy a city we bade the opulent ones thereof; and they wrought abomination therein; and its due sentence was pronounced; and we destroyed it with utter destruction
  17,17,"How many generations have we destroyed after Noah! but thy Lord of the sins of his servant is well aware, and sees enough"
  17,18,"Whoso is desirous of this life that hastens away, we will hasten on for him therein what we please,- for whom we please. Then we will make hell for him to broil in - despised and outcast"
  17,19,"But whoso desires the next life, and strives for it and is a believer - these, their striving shall be gratefully received"
  17,20,To all - these and those - will we extend the gifts of thy Lord; for the gifts of thy Lord are not restricted
  17,21,"See how we have preferred some of them over others, but in the next life are greater degrees and greater preference"
  17,22,"Put not with God other gods, or thou wilt sit despised and forsaken"
  17,23,"Thy Lord has decreed that ye shall not serve other than Him; and kindness to one's parents, whether one or both of them reach old age with thee; and say not to them, 'Fie!' and do not grumble at them, but speak to them a generous speech"
  17,24,"And lower to them the wing of humility out of compassion, and say, 'O Lord! have compassion on them as they brought me up when I was little"
  17,25,"Your Lord knows best what is in your souls if ye be righteous, and, verily, He is forgiving unto those who come back penitent"
  17,26,And give thy kinsman his due and the poor and the son of the road; and waste not wastefully
  17,27,for the wasteful were ever the devil's brothers; and the devil is ever ungrateful to his Lord
  17,28,"But if thou dost turn away from them to seek after mercy from thy Lord, which thou hopest for, then speak to them an easy speech"
  17,29,"Make not thy hand fettered to thy neck, nor yet spread it out quite open, lest thou shouldst have to sit down blamed and straitened in means"
  17,30,"Verily, thy Lord spreads out provision to whomsoever He will or He doles it out. Verily, He is ever well aware of and sees His servants"
  17,31,And slay not your children for fear of poverty; we will provide for them; beware! for to slay them is ever a great sin
  17,32,"And draw not near to fornication; verily, it is ever an abomination, and evil is the way thereof"
  17,33,"And slay not the soul that God has forbidden you, except for just cause; for he who is slain unjustly we have given his next of kin authority; yet let him not exceed in slaying; verily, he is ever helped"
  17,34,"And draw not near to the wealth of the orphan, save to improve it, until he reaches the age of puberty, and fulfil your compacts; verily, a compact is ever enquired of"
  17,35,"And give full measure when ye measure out, and weigh with a right balance; that is better and a fairer determination"
  17,36,"And do not pursue that of which thou hast no knowledge; verily, the hearing, the sight, and the heart, all of these shall be enquired of"
  17,37,"And walk not on the earth proudly; verily, thou canst not cleave the earth, and thou shalt not reach the mountains in height"
  17,38,All this is ever evil in the sight of your Lord and abhorred
  17,39,"That is something of what thy Lord has inspired thee with of wisdom; do not then put with God other gods, or thou wilt be thrown into hell reproached and outcast"
  17,40,"What! has your Lord chosen to give you sons, and shall He take for Himself females from among the angels? verily, ye are speaking a mighty speech"
  17,41,"Now have we turned it in various ways in this Qur'an, so let them bear in mind; but it will only increase them in aversion"
  17,42,"Say, 'Were there with Him other gods, as ye say, then would they seek a way against the Lord of the throne"
  17,43,"Celebrated be His praises, and exalted be He above what they say with a great exaltation"
  17,44,"The seven heavens and the earth celebrate His praises, and all who therein are; nor is there aught, but what celebrates His praise: but ye cannot understand their celebration;- verily, He is clement and forgiving"
  17,45,And when thou readest the Qur'an we place between thee and those who believe not in the hereafter a covering veil
  17,46,"And we place covers upon their hearts, lest they should understand, and dulness in their ears. And when thou dost mention in the Qur'an thy Lord by Himself they turn their backs in aversion"
  17,47,"We know best for what they listen when they listen to thee; and when they whisper apart - when the wrongdoers say, 'Ye only follow a man enchanted"
  17,48,"Behold, how they strike out for you parables, and err, and cannot find the way"
  17,49,"They say, 'What! when we have become bones and rubbish are we to be raised up a new creature"
  17,50,"Say, 'Be ye stones, or iron"
  17,51,"or a creature, the greatest your breasts can conceive -!' Then they shall say, 'Who is to restore us?' Say, 'He who originated you at first;' and they will wag their heads and say, 'When will that be?' Say, 'It may, perhaps, be nigh"
  17,52,"The day when He shall call on you and ye shall answer with praise to Him, and they will think that they have tarried but a little"
  17,53,"And say to my servants that they speak in a kind way; verily, Satan makes ill-will between them; verily, Satan was ever unto man an open foe"
  17,54,"Your Lord knows you best; if He please He will have mercy upon you, or if He please He will torment you: but we, have not sent thee to take charge of them"
  17,55,"And thy Lord best knows who is in the heavens and the earth; we did prefer some of the prophets over the others, and to David did we give the Psalms"
  17,56,"Say, 'Call on those whom ye pretend other than God;' but they shall not have the power to remove distress from you, nor to turn it off"
  17,57,"Those on whom they call, seek themselves for a means of approaching their Lord, (to see) which of them is nearest: and they hope for His mercy and they fear His torment; verily, the torment of thy Lord is a thing to beware of"
  17,58,"There is no city but we will destroy it before the day of judgment, or torment it with keen torment;- that is in the Book inscribed"
  17,59,"Naught hindered us from sending thee with signs, save that those of yore said they were lies; so we gave Thamud the visible she-camel, but they treated her unjustly! for we do not send (any one) with signs save to make men fear"
  17,60,"And when we said to thee, 'Verily, thy Lord encompasses men!' and we made the vision which we showed thee only a cause of sedition unto men, and the cursed tree as well; for we will frighten them, but it will only increase them in great rebellion"
  17,61,"And when we said to the angels, ' Adore Adam;' and they adored, save Iblis, who said, ' Am I to adore one whom Thou hast created out of clay"
  17,62,"Said he, 'Dost thou see now? this one whom Thou hast honoured above me, verily, if Thou shouldst respite me until the resurrection day, I will of a surety utterly destroy his seed except a few"
  17,63,"Said He, 'Begone! and whoso of them follows thee - verily, hell is your recompense, an ample recompense"
  17,64,"Entice away whomsoever of them thou canst with thy voice; and bear down upon them with thy horse and with thy foot; and share with them in their wealth and their children; and promise them,- but Satan promises them naught but deceit"
  17,65,"Verily, my servants, thou hast no authority over them; thy Lord is guardian enough over them"
  17,66,"It is your Lord who drives the ships for you in the sea that ye may seek after plenty from Him; verily, He is ever merciful to you"
  17,67,"And when distress touches you in the sea, those whom ye call on, except Him, stray away from you; but when He has brought you safe to shore, ye turn away; for man is ever ungrateful"
  17,68,"Are ye sure that He will not cleave with you the side of the shore, or send against you a heavy sand-storm? then ye will find no guardian for yourselves"
  17,69,"Or are ye sure that He will not send you back therein another time, and send against you a violent wind, and drown you for your misbelief? then ye will find for yourselves no protector against us"
  17,70,"But, we have been gracious to the children of Adam, and we have borne them by land and sea, and have provided them with good things, and have preferred them over many that we have created"
  17,71,"The day when we will call all men by their high priest; and he whose book is given in his right hand - these shall read their book, nor shall they be wronged a straw"
  17,72,"But he who in this life is blind shall be blind in the next too, and err farther from the way"
  17,73,"They had well-nigh beguiled thee from what we inspired thee with, that thou shouldst forge against us something else, and then they would have taken thee for a friend"
  17,74,"and had it not been that we established thee, thou wouldst have well-nigh leant towards them a little"
  17,75,"then would we have made thee taste of torment both of life and death, then thou wouldst not have found against us any helper"
  17,76,"And they well-nigh enticed thee away from the land, to turn thee out therefrom; but then - they should not have tarried after thee except a little"
  17,77,"[This is] the course of those of our prophets whom we have sent before thee; and thou shalt find no change in our course"
  17,78,"Be thou steadfast in prayer from the declining of the sun until the dusk of the night, and the reading of the dawn; verily, the reading of the dawn is ever testified to"
  17,79,"And for the night, watch thou therein as an extra service. It may be that thy Lord will raise thee to a laudable station"
  17,80,"And say, 'O my Lord! make me enter with a just entry; and make me come forth with a just coming forth; and grant me from, Thee authority to aid"
  17,81,"And say, 'Truth has come, and falsehood has vanished! verily, falsehood is transient"
  17,82,"And we will send down of the Qur'an that which is a healing and a mercy to the believers, but it will only increase the wrong-doers in loss"
  17,83,"And when we favour man he turns away and retires aside, but when evil touches him he is ever in despair"
  17,84,"Say, 'Every one acts after his own manner, but your Lord knows, best who is most guided in the way"
  17,85,"They will ask thee of the spirit. Say, 'The spirit comes at the bidding of my Lord, and ye are given but a little knowledge thereof"
  17,86,If we had wished we would have taken away that with which we have inspired thee; then thou wouldst have found no guardian against us
  17,87,"unless by a mercy from thy Lord; verily, His grace towards thee is great"
  17,88,"Say, 'If mankind and ginns united together to bring the like of this Qur'an, they could not bring the like, though they should back each other up"
  17,89,"We have turned about for men in this Qur'an every parable; but most men refuse to accept it, save ungratefully"
  17,90,"And they say, 'We will by no means believe in thee, until there gush forth for thee a fountain from the earth"
  17,91,"or there be made for thee a garden of palms and grapes, and rivers come gushing out amidst them"
  17,92,or thou make the sky to fall down upon us in pieces; or thou bring us God and the angels before us
  17,93,"or there be made for thee a house of gold; or thou climb up into the heaven; and even then we will not believe in thy climbing there, until thou send down on us a book that we may read!' Say, 'Celebrated be the praises of my Lord! was I aught but a mortal apostle"
  17,94,"Naught prohibited men from believing when the guidance came to them, save their saying, 'God has sent a mortal for an apostle"
  17,95,"Say, 'Were there angels on the earth walking in quiet, we had surely sent them an angel as an apostle"
  17,96,"Say, 'God is witness enough between me and you; verily, He is ever of His servants well aware, and sees"
  17,97,"He whom God guides, he is guided indeed; and he whom God leads astray, thou shalt never find patrons for them beside Him; and we will gather them upon the resurrection day upon their faces, blind, and dumb, and deaf; their resort is hell; whenever it grows dull we will give them another blaze"
  17,98,"That is their reward for that they disbelieved in our signs, and said, 'What! when we are bones and rubbish, shall we then be raised up a new creation"
  17,99,"Could they not see that God who created the heavens and the earth is able to create the like of them, and to set for them an appointed time; there is no doubt therein, yet the wrong-doers refuse to accept it, save ungratefully"
  17,100,"Say, 'Did ye control the treasuries of the mercy of my Lord, then ye would hold them through fear of expending; for man is ever niggardly"
  17,101,"And we did bring Moses nine manifest signs; then ask the children of Israel (about) when he came to them, and Pharaoh said to him, 'Verily, I think thee, O Moses! enchanted"
  17,102,"He said, 'Well didst thou know that none sent down these save the Lord of the heavens and the earth as visible signs; and, verily, I think thee, O Pharaoh! ruined"
  17,103,"And he desired to drive them out of the land; but we drowned him and those with him, one and all"
  17,104,"And after him we said to the children of Israel, 'Dwell ye in the land; and when the promise of the hereafter comes to pass, we will bring you in a mixed crowd (to judgment)"
  17,105,"In truth have we sent it down, and in truth has it come down; and we have not sent thee as aught but a herald of glad tidings and a warner"
  17,106,"And a Qur'an which we have divided, that thou mayst read it to mankind leisurely, and we sent it down, sending it down"
  17,107,"Say, 'Believe ye therein, or believe not; verily, those who were given the knowledge before it, when it is read to them fall down upon their beards adoring"
  17,108,"and they say, \"Celebrated be the praises of our Lord! verily, the promise of our Lord is ever fulfilled"
  17,109,"they fall down upon their beards weeping, and it increases their humility"
  17,110,"Say, 'Call on God, or call on the Merciful One, whichever ye may call on Him by; for His are the best of names.' And do not say thy prayers openly, nor yet murmur them, but seek a way between these"
  17,111,"And say, 'Praise belongs to God, who has not taken to Himself a son, and has not had a partner in His kingdom, nor had a patron against (such) abasement.' And magnify Him greatly"
  18,1,"Praise belongs to God, who sent down to His servant the Book and put no crookedness therein"
  18,2,"straight, to give warning of keen violence from Him; and to give the glad tidings to the believers, who do what is right, that for them is a goodly reward"
  18,3,wherein they shall abide for ever and for aye
  18,4,"and to give warning to those who say, 'God hath taken to Himself a son"
  18,5,"They have no knowledge thereof, nor their fathers; a serious word it is that comes forth from their mouths! verily, they only speak a lie"
  18,6,"Haply thou wilt grieve thyself to death for sorrow after them, if they believe not in this new revelation"
  18,7,"Verily, we have made what is on the earth an ornament thereof, to try them, which of them is best in works"
  18,8,"but, verily, we are going to make what is thereon bare soil"
  18,9,Hast thou reckoned that the Fellows of the Cave and Er-raqim were a wonder amongst our signs
  18,10,"When the youths resorted to the cave and said, 'O our Lord! bring us mercy from Thee, and dispose for us our affair aright"
  18,11,And we struck their ears (with deafness) in the cave for a number of years
  18,12,"Then we raised them up again, that we might know which of the two crews could best calculate the time of their tarrying"
  18,13,"We will narrate to thee their story in truth. Verily, they were youths who believed in their Lord, and we added to their guidance"
  18,14,"and we braced up their hearts, when they stood up and said, 'Our Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, we will not call upon any god beside Him, for then we should have said an extravagant thing"
  18,15,These people of ours have taken to other gods beside Him. Though they do not bring any manifest authority for them. And who is more unjust than he who forges against God a lie
  18,16,"So when ye have gone apart from them and what they serve other than God, then resort ye to the cave. Our Lord will unfold His mercy to you, and will dispose for you your affair advantageously"
  18,17,"And thou mightst have seen the sun when it rose decline from their cave towards the right hand, and when it set leave them on the left hand, while they were in the spacious part thereof. That is one of the signs of God. Whom God guides he is guided indeed, and whom He leads astray thou shalt surely find for him no patron to guide aright"
  18,18,"Thou mightst have reckoned them waking though they were sleeping, as we turned them towards the right and towards the left; and their dog spreading out his fore-paws on the threshold. Hadst thou come suddenly upon them thou wouldst surely have turned and fled away from them, and wouldst surely have been filled by them with dread"
  18,19,"Thus did we raise them up that they might question each other. Spake a speaker amongst them, 'How long have ye tarried?' They said, 'We have tarried a day or part of a day.' They said, 'Your Lord knows best your tarrying; so send one of you with this coin of yours to the city, and let him look which of them has purest food, and let him bring you provision thereof; and let him be subtle and not let any one perceive you"
  18,20,"Verily, they - should they perceive you - would stone you, or would force you back again unto their faith, and ye would never prosper then"
  18,21,"Thus did we make their people acquainted with their story, that they might know that God's promise is true; and that the Hour, there is no doubt concerning it. When they disputed amongst themselves concerning their affair, and said, 'Build a building over them, their Lord knows best about them;' and those who prevailed in their affair said, 'We will surely make a mosque over them"
  18,22,"They will say, 'Three, and the fourth of them was their dog:' and they will say, 'Five, and the sixth of them was their dog:' guessing at the unseen: and they will say, 'Seven, and the eighth of them was their dog.' Say, 'My Lord knows best the number of them; none knows them but few.' Dispute not therefore concerning them save with a plain disputation, and ask not any one of them concerning them"
  18,23,"And never say of anything, 'Verily, I am going to do that to-morrow"
  18,24,"except 'if God please;' and remember thy Lord when thou hast forgotten, and say,' It may be that my Lord will guide me to what is nearer to the right than this"
  18,25,They tarried in their cave three hundred years and nine more
  18,26,"Say, 'God knows best of their tarrying. His are the unseen things of the heavens and the earth - He can see! and hear!' They have no patron beside Him, nor does He let any one share in His judgment"
  18,27,"So, recite what thou art inspired with of the Book of thy Lord; there is no changing His words; nor shalt thou ever find a refuge beside Him"
  18,28,"and keep thyself patient, with those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, desiring His face; nor let thine eyes be turned from them, desiring the adornment of the life of this world; and obey not him whose heart we have made heedless of remembrance of us, and who follows his lusts, for his affair is ever in advance (of the truth)"
  18,29,"But say, 'The truth is from your Lord, so let him who will, believe; and let him who will, disbelieve.' Verily, we have prepared for the evildoers a fire, sheets of which shall encompass them; and if they cry for help, they shall be helped with water like molten brass, which shall roast their faces: - an ill drink and an evil couch"
  18,30,"Verily, those who believe and act aright,- verily, we will not waste the hire of him who does good works"
  18,31,"These, for them are gardens of Eden; beneath them rivers flow; they shall be adorned therein with bracelets of gold, and shall wear green robes of silk, and of brocade; reclining therein on thrones;- pleasant is the reward, and goodly the couch"
  18,32,"Strike out for them a parable: Two men, for one of whom we made two gardens of grapes, and surrounded them with palms, and put corn between the two"
  18,33,Each of the two gardens brought forth its food and did not fail in aught. And we caused a river to gush forth amidst them
  18,34,"and he had fruit, and said unto his fellow, who was his next-door neighbour, 'I am more wealthy than thee, and mightier of household"
  18,35,"And he went in unto his garden, having wronged himself: said he, 'I do not think that this will ever disappear"
  18,36,"and I do not think that the hour is imminent; and if even I be sent back unto my Lord, I shall find a better one than it in exchange"
  18,37,"Said unto him his fellow, who was his next-door neighbour, 'Thou hast disbelieved in Him who created thee from earth, and then from a clot, then fashioned thee a man"
  18,38,"but, God, He is my Lord; nor will I associate any one with my Lord"
  18,39,"Why couldst thou not have said, when thou didst go into thy garden, \"What God pleases! there is no power save in God,\" - to look at, I am less than thee in wealth and children"
  18,40,"but haply my Lord will give me something better than thy garden, and will send upon it thunder-claps from the sky, and it shall be on the morrow bare slippery soil"
  18,41,"or on the morrow its water may be deeply sunk, so that thou canst not get thereat"
  18,42,"And his fruits were encompassed, and on the morrow he turned down the palms of his hands for what he had spent thereon, for it was fallen down upon its trellises. And he said, 'Would that I had never associated any one with my Lord"
  18,43,"And he had not any party to help him beside God, nor was he helped"
  18,44,"In such a case the patronage is God's, the true; He is best at rewarding and best at bringing to an issue"
  18,45,"Strike out for them, too, a parable of the life of this world; like water which we send down from the sky, and the vegetation of the earth is mingled therewith; - and on the morrow it is dried up, and the winds scatter it; for God is powerful over all"
  18,46,"Wealth and children are an adornment of the life of this world; but enduring good works are better with thy Lord, as a recompense, and better as a hope"
  18,47,"And the day when we will move the mountains, and thou shalt see the (whole) earth stalking forth; and we will gather them, and will not leave one of them behind"
  18,48,"Then shall they be presented to thy Lord in ranks. - Now have ye come to us as we created you at first! nay, but ye thought that we would never make our promise good"
  18,49,"And the Book shall be placed, and thou shalt see the sinners in fear of what is in it; and they will say, ' Alas, for us! what ails this Book, it leaves neither small nor great things alone, without numbering them?' and they shall find present what they have done; and thy Lord will not wrong any one"
  18,50,"And when we said to the angels, ' Adore Adam,' they adored him, save only Iblis, who was of the ginn, who revolted from the bidding of his Lord. 'What! will ye then take him and his seed as patrons, rather than me, when they are foes of yours? bad for the wrong-doers is the exchange"
  18,51,"I did not make them witnesses of the creation of the heavens and the earth, nor of the creation of themselves, nor did I take those who lead astray for my supporters"
  18,52,"On the day when He shall say, 'Call ye my partners whom ye pretend:' and they shall call on them, but they shall not answer them; and we will set the vale of perdition between them"
  18,53,"and the sinners shall see the fire, and shall think that they are going to fall therein, and shall find no escape therefrom"
  18,54,We have turned about in this Qur'an for men every parable; but man is ever at most things a caviller
  18,55,"Naught prevented men from believing when the guidance came to them, or from asking pardon of their Lord, except the coming on them of the course of those of yore, or the coming of the torment before their eyes"
  18,56,We sent not prophets save as heralds of glad tidings and as warners; but those who misbelieve wrangle with vain speech to make void the truth therewith; and they take my signs and the warnings given them as a jest
  18,57,"Who is more unjust than he who, being reminded of the signs of his Lord, turns away therefrom, and forgets what his hands have done before? verily, we will place veils upon their hearts lest they should understand, and dullness in their ears! And if thou shouldst call them to the guidance, they will not be guided then for ever"
  18,58,"But thy Lord is forgiving, endowed with mercy; were He to punish them for what they have earned He would have hastened for them the torment. Nay rather, they have their appointed time, and shall never find a refuge beside Him"
  18,59,"These cities, we destroyed them when they were unjust; and for their destruction we set an appointed time"
  18,60,"And when Moses said to his servant, 'I will not cease until I reach the confluence of the two seas, or else I will go on for years"
  18,61,"But when they reached the confluence of the two they forgot their fish, and it took its way in the sea with a free course"
  18,62,"And when they had passed by, he said to his servant, 'Bring us our dinners, for we have met with toil from this journey of ours"
  18,63,"Said he, 'What thinkest thou? when we resorted to the rock, then, verily, I forgot the fish, but it was only Satan who made me forget it, lest I should remember it; and it took its way in the set wondrously"
  18,64,"Said he, 'This is what we were searching for.' So they turned back upon their footsteps, following them up"
  18,65,"Then they found a servant of our servants, to whom we had given mercy from ourselves, and had taught him knowledge from before us"
  18,66,"Said Moses to him, 'Shall I follow thee, so that thou mayest teach me, from what thou hast been taught, the right way"
  18,67,"said he, 'Verily, thou canst never have patience with me"
  18,68,How canst thou be patient in what thou comprehendest no knowledge of
  18,69,"He said, 'Thou wilt find me, if God will, patient; nor will I rebel against thy bidding"
  18,70,"He said, 'Then, if thou followest me, ask me not about anything until I begin for them the mention of it"
  18,71,"So they set out until when they rode in the bark, he scuttled it. Said he, 'Hast thou scuttled it to drown its crew? Thou hast produced a strange thing"
  18,72,"Said he, 'Did I not tell thee, verily, thou canst never have patience with me"
  18,73,"Said he, 'Rebuke me not for forgetting, and impose not on me a difficult command"
  18,74,"So they set out until they met a boy, and he killed him. And he (Moses) said, 'Hast thou killed a pure person without (his killing) a person? thou hast produced an unheard-of thing"